page.text: Arterial Travel Time and Delay Analyses
WorldTech Engineering has been retained by the Town of Brookline to perform a quantitative and
qualitative analysis of the positive and negative effects of a pedestrian actuated signal at the crosswalk
on Harvard Street at Green Street. The analysis considers the impacts on traffic conditions at the
intersection of Harvard Street and Beacon Street, as well as the impact on traffic along the Harvard Street
corridor between Beacon Street and Babcock Street.
The results of the study show that a pedestrian signal at this location, if coordinated with the signals at
Beacon Street and at Babcock Street, and if strictly obeyed by pedestrians, has the ability to improve
vehicular progression through the corridor. However, in practice, pedestrians would likely disobey the
signal due to the inherent delays resulting from the coordinated signal system. Alternative measures have
been identified, described herein, that would provide greater benefits to traffic progression along Harvard
Street as well as help to better manage pedestrian crossings at the Green Street intersection.
In addition, the feasibility of changing the lane assignment along the northbound Harvard Street approach
at Beacon Street was explored. Currently, the approach consists of one through lane and one shared
through/right turn lane, with northbound traffic along Harvard Street merging to a single lane north of
Beacon Street. To eliminate this bottleneck, an alternative was analyzed to convert the shared
through/right turn lane to an exclusive right turn lane, removing the merge north of the intersection. The
resulting capacity analysis demonstrated that a single northbound lane is insufficient for the northbound
through movement and would result in unacceptable delays and queues along Harvard Street south of
Existing roadway and traffic conditions in the study area were determined based on field visits and
development of a comprehensive traffic count program. The existing transportation conditions in the
study area, including roadway geometrics, traffic controls, peak hour traffic flows, and traffic safety data
are described below. The study area is shown in Figure 1.
Within the study corridor Harvard Street is classified as an Urban Principal Arterial travelling in a
generally northwest-southeast direction. Harvard Street connects the Brookline Village area of
Brookline with the Allston neighborhood of Boston. Harvard Street consists of one 14 foot travel
lane in each direction separated by a double yellow center line. Six-foot wide bike lanes are
present on both shoulders of the roadway adjacent to an 8 foot parking lane. There is a sidewalk
present on both sides of the roadway. Land use along Harvard Street is primarily commercial.
Babcock Street intersects Harvard Street from the northeast to form a signalized T-type
intersection. One through lane and one turning lane are provided on each approach of Harvard
Street, while separate left and right-turn lanes are provided on Babcock Street. Double yellow
lines separate directional flow on both streets. Crosswalks are provided across each leg of the
intersection, with pedestrian push buttons and emergency vehicle preemption equipment
included as part of the existing signal setup. Brookline Fire Station 5 is located on Babcock Street
approximately 500 feet from the intersection. Land use at the intersection is primarily commercial
and retail. Curb extensions are present on all corners of the intersection with the exception of the
north corner in front of Citizens Bank.
Green Street intersects Harvard Street from the northeast to form an unsignalized T-type
intersection. One through lane is provided on each approach of Harvard Street, while Green Street
is restricted to one-way traffic away from the intersection. Green Street provides one travel lane,
one bike lane and one parking lane. Double yellow lines separate directional flow on Harvard
Street, and bollards along the Harvard Street centerline physically prohibit vehicles from turning
left from southbound Harvard Street into Green Street, or from northbound Harvard Street into
the municipal parking lot entrance adjacent to Coolidge Corner Opticians. Crosswalks are provided
across Green Street and the northwest leg of Harvard Street. No curb extensions are present on
any corner of the intersection. Land use at the intersection is primarily commercial and retail. On-
street parking is allowed on Harvard Street, except along the approach to the intersection from
Beacon Street, where the parking was removed to allow for a second travel lane that merges into
a single lane at the intersection with Green Street.
Harvard Street and Beacon Street meet to form a 4-way signalized intersection. The C-Cleveland
Circle branch of the MBTAâ€™s Green Line light rail runs along the median of Beacon Street. The
inbound (eastbound) platform is located west of the Harvard Street intersection, while the
outbound (westbound) platform is located east of the intersection. Beacon Street provides two
travel lanes in each direction, with an additional right-turn-only lane in each direction at the
intersection. Left turns from Beacon Street onto Harvard Street are prohibited in both directions.
Harvard Street provides two travel lanes in each direction, with left turns prohibited onto Beacon
Street in both directions. Crosswalks are provided across all legs of the intersection, along with
pedestrian push buttons and signal heads. Land use at the intersection is primarily commercial
In order to quantify existing traffic volume conditions in the project study area, automatic traffic
recorder (ATR) counts and manual turning movement counts (TMC) were conducted in June 2014
to supplement data collected in 2009 and 2011. ATR counts were conducted along Harvard Street
and Green Street for a 72-hour period to record hourly traffic volumes within the study area on
both weekdays and a Saturday. TMCs were conducted at the study area intersections during the
normal weekday morning peak period (7:00 to 9:00 AM), weekday evening peak period (4:00 to
6:00 PM), and Saturday midday peak period (12:00 to 2:00 PM).
Evaluation of the peak period traffic counts indicates that the weekday morning peak hour
generally occurs from 7:45 to 8:45 AM and the weekday evening peak hour generally occurs from
5:00 to 6:00 PM. It should be noted that the individual peak hour traffic volumes at each
intersection were used to provide a conservative analysis scenario. The traffic count data is

type of roadway. To determine if the data should be adjusted to account for this fluctuation, traffic

traffic volumes during June are approximately 10 percent higher than the average yearly volumes
for similar roadways. Recognizing this, in order to provide a slightly conservative analysis traffic

In addition to vehicular volumes, the volume of pedestrians using the crosswalks during the peak
hours was also recorded. The volume of pedestrians crossing Harvard Street, Babcock Street,
Green Street and Beacon Street in each crosswalk was observed and are shown in Figure 3. The
crosswalks at the intersection of Beacon Street and Harvard Street carry the highest pedestrian
volumes, with 250 to 650 pedestrians per hour. The crosswalk on Harvard Street at Green Street
carries 200 pedestrians during the morning peak hour, with 320 pedestrians during the afternoon
peak hour and 540 pedestrians during the Saturday peak hour. The crosswalk across Green Street
is very heavily used, with 350 to 630 pedestrians during the peak hours.

A total of 64 crashes occurred within the study area roadways, 31 of which occurred at the
intersection of Beacon Street and Harvard Street. A review of the crash data indicates only 3
crashes occurred at the intersection of Harvard Street and Green Street. Within the study area,
pedestrians were involved in 7 crashes, with bicycles involved in 4 crashes and parked cars in 7
crashes. Only one pedestrian crash occurred at the Green Street intersection during the 5 year
To evaluate the crashes at an intersection effectively, the number of crashes must relate or be
compared to the traffic volumes entering the intersection. A procedure used for this purpose is
the calculation of an intersection crash rate, which is a measure of the frequency of crashes
compared to the intersection traffic volumes. The crash rate is based on crashes per million
entering vehicles (C/MEV). MassDOT releases official Statewide and District rates that can be used
as an effective tool to compare safety hazards at a specific intersection. The latest Statewide and
District 6 rates for unsignalized intersections are 0.60 and 0.58 C/MEV, respectively. For signalized
intersections, the Statewide and District 6 rates are 0.80 and 0.76 C/MEV, respectively. Crash rates
higher than these averages could indicate a potential safety issue. The crash rate worksheets have
been provided in the Technical Appendix.

A pedestrian signal warrants analysis was conducted for the pedestrian crossing of Harvard Street
at Green Street using traffic and pedestrian volume data collected for this study. A signal warrants
analysis is used to help determine if a traffic signal installation is justified at a location. Traffic
signal warrants are defined in the Manual on Uniform Traffic Control Devices (MUTCD), 2009
Edition published by Federal Highway Administration. The MUTCD specifies minimum
requirements for any of eight (8) different warrants under which a traffic signal may be installed
at an intersection. Traffic control signals should not be installed unless one or more of the
warrants in the MUTCD are satisfied. The satisfaction of a warrant or warrants is not in itself
justification for a signal installation. It also needs to be determined that a traffic signal will improve
the overall safety and/or operation of the intersection. Warrant 4, pedestrian volume, is the signal
warrant that is applicable to this situation. One of two criteria should be met before considering
a signal based solely on pedestrian volumes. The two criteria include minimum pedestrian and
vehicle volumes over the four highest hours, and the pedestrian and vehicle volumes during the
Detailed traffic signal warrant analyses were conducted based on existing traffic volumes at the
Green Street crossing. Based on the analyses, the crossing meets the peak hour criteria but not
the four-hour criteria. However, the MUTCD stipulates that the pedestrian volume warrant shall
not be applied at locations where the distance to the nearest traffic control signal is less than 300
feet, unless the proposed traffic signal will not restrict the progressive flow of traffic. Therefore,
coordinated traffic signal control along the Harvard Street corridor was investigated as part of the
alternatives analysis for this report. The warrant analysis worksheets are provided in the Technical
The C-Cleveland Circle branch of the MBTAâ€™s Green Line light rail runs along the median of Beacon
Street, with the Coolidge Corner station located at the Harvard Street intersection. The inbound
(eastbound) platform is located west of the Harvard Street intersection, while the outbound
(westbound) platform is located east of the intersection. The Coolidge Corner station is the most
used station on the Cleveland Circle branch, with 3,440 daily station entries on a typical weekday
(2014 MBTA Blue Book). Trains operate on 7 minute headways during weekday peak periods and
8 to 14 minute headways during off-peak times.
The Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority (MBTA) operates a bus route (Route 66, Harvard
Square â€“ Dudley Station) along Harvard Street. This route, the third-heaviest in the MBTA system
by ridership, operates with headways of 10 to 20 minutes on weekdays and Saturdays.
Bus stops are located on Harvard Street at its intersection with Beacon Street. The southbound
stop (stop #1308) is located north of Beacon Street, while the northbound stop (stop #1372) is
located south of Beacon Street. Based on ridership counts conducted by the MBTA in fall 2009,
the northbound stop recorded 327 boardings and 468 alightings on a typical weekday, while the
southbound stop saw 475 boardings and 396 alightings.
Stops at Babcock Street were eliminated in 2013 as part of the MBTA Key Bus Route Improvement
Program. Prior to elimination, 50 passengers boarded and 137 passengers alighted in the
northbound direction, and 196 passengers boarded and 89 alighted in the southbound direction
Route 66 bus at Babcock Street on a typical weekday based on fall 2009 MBTA ridership counts.
These riders are anticipated to use new stops located at Harvard Street and Shailer Street,
Crosswalks are marked across all signal-controlled approaches throughout the study area, and a
single crosswalk is provided to cross Harvard Street at its intersection with Green Street. The
crosswalk at Green Street is a standard (MUTCD) crosswalk with white transverse and longitudinal
lines. This crosswalk has a â€œYield Here to Pedestriansâ€ sign (MUTCD R1-5) in the center of Harvard
Street to warn drivers of pedestrians crossing the roadway. All signalized pedestrian crossings are
equipped with pedestrian push buttons, pedestrian signal heads, and concurrent pedestrian
phasing with a leading pedestrian indication for all crossings.
Within the study area, on-street parking is provided along both sides of Harvard Street north of
Green Street, and along the south side of Harvard Street south of Green Street. The parking is
metered and restricted to a 2-hour time limit. At the Green Street crosswalk, parking is restricted
within 20 feet of each side of the crosswalk, with an MBTA bus stop located on the south side of
Harvard Street immediately south of the crosswalk.
Existing peak hour traffic operations in the traffic study area were assessed from both a quantitative and
qualitative perspective. The qualitative analysis is based on field observations made during peak traffic
periods, while the quantitative analysis is based on calculated intersection operating levels of service as
The capacity analysis methodology is based on the concepts and procedures described in the â€œHighway
Capacity Manualâ€ (HCM), 2000, Transportation Research Board, Washington, DC. A capacity analysis is
used to assess the quality of traffic operations on a roadway or intersection as a result of traffic volume
demands placed on the respective facility. The primary result of a capacity analysis is a level of service
(LOS) assignment to the traffic operations of the respective facility. A LOS analysis results in assigning a
letter index of A through F to describe the quality of traffic operations at a facility in terms of such factors
as speed, traffic interruptions, freedom to maneuver, comfort, convenience and safety. The six letter
designations of A through F define the operating conditions from best to worst, respectively. In general,
a LOS C is used as the minimum design criteria although D is acceptable at urban, high volume locations.
LOS for either signalized or unsignalized intersections can be computed by the described methodology.
LOS for signalized intersections is defined in terms of delay, which is a measure of driver discomfort,
frustration, fuel consumption and lost travel time. The delay experienced by a motorist is made of factors
that relate to intersection control, geometrics and traffic volumes. This delay is called â€œcontrol delayâ€ or
â€œsignal delayâ€. Control delay includes initial deceleration delay, queue move-up time, stopped delay and
final acceleration delay. Specifically, LOS criteria at an intersection with traffic signals are stated in terms
of the average control delay per vehicle.
The LOS for an unsignalized intersection (two-way stop control) is defined for each minor movement, not
for the intersection as a whole. The LOS criteria for the unsignalized intersections are somewhat different
from the criteria for the signalized intersections. The primary reason for the difference is that motorists
expect different levels of performance from the two facilities. Due to these expectations, the control delay
threshold for any given LOS is less for an unsignalized intersection than it is for a signalized intersection.
Table 6 summarizes the LOS criteria associated with the letter index and the relationship between
signalized and unsignalized intersections. The LOS delay criteria may be applied to individual lane groups,
to individual intersection approaches or to the entire signalized or unsignalized intersections.

Level of Service (LOS) analyses were performed for the study area intersections under various conditions
to arrive at proposed optimal improvements. The unsignalized and signalized intersection methodology
was used to evaluate the various alternatives. To reiterate, the unsignalized intersection methodology
evaluates only the conflict movements, that is, the major street left turns and the minor street
approaches. It does not assign a LOS to the intersection as a whole.
In addition to level of service, a review of the 95
percentile queue lengths was performed during each of
the peak hours under existing conditions. While an intersection may show acceptable levels of service,
extensive queue lengths may exist that impede operations elsewhere by extending into adjacent
intersections or other conflict areas. A description of the critical queues at each intersection location is
In addition to LOS, another factor to take into consideration when discussing operation is the â€œvolume-to-
capacityâ€ ratio. The volume-to-capacity (v/c) ratio is the ratio of the volume travelling in a lane group to
the capacity of the same lane group, a percentage of the lane groupâ€™s capacity being utilized. As with
delay, this measure can be utilized for either the individual approach or the intersection as a whole. As
opposed to delay there is no standard gauge to provide a specific point of reference for a certain volume-
to-capacity ratio; however a lower volume-to-capacity ratio indicates that backups are less likely. As the
v/c ratio approaches 1.0, the operation worsens since the facility is reaching capacity. A volume-to-
capacity ratio of 1.0 or greater indicates traffic volumes are exceeding capacity. Generally speaking, a
volume-to-capacity ratio under 1.0 is considered acceptable.

Three alternatives were studied to improve the flow of vehicles through the Harvard Street
corridor, and to reduce conflicts between vehicles and pedestrians at the Green Street crosswalk.
The first alternative consists of the installation of a pedestrian actuated signal at the Green Street
crossing. The second alternative is the development of new traffic signal coordination patterns
without the installation of the pedestrian signal. The third alternative looks into the operations of
the Harvard Street and Beacon Street intersection if the Harvard Street NB approach lane use
changed from a through lane and through/right lane to an exclusive through lane and exclusive
right turn lane. Curb extensions at Harvard Street and Green Street intersection are also
considered, but do not affect the intersection operations analysis.

text.i: Alternative 1 â€“ Pedestrian Actuated Signal at Green Street crosswalk

page.text: A signal at the pedestrian crossing could improve traffic flow through the corridor, but only if
pedestrians strictly obeyed the signal and did not jaywalk or cross when the signal is in Donâ€™t Walk
mode. However, the close proximity of the new pedestrian signal to the existing signalized
intersection of Beacon Street at Harvard Street would require that the two signals be
interconnected to allow them to operate in coordination. Coordination would prevent queues
from one intersection from blocking the other intersection by allowing the pedestrian signal to
only be activated when Beacon Street traffic has a green light. As a result, the pedestrian signal
would not be immediately responsive to pedestrian activation, unless the button was pressed
shortly before Beacon Street was to receive its green signal. A significant problem with this
requirement is that pedestrians could experience delay times of 35-40 seconds between the time
the pedestrian button is pushed and when the pedestrian walk signal comes on. This delay would
not meet pedestrian expectations; pedestrians would likely grow frustrated, thinking the signal
isnâ€™t working properly, and would likely cross Harvard Street without waiting for the signal to
change. This would result in increased delays for motorists as they yield to jaywalking pedestrians,
and then have to stop fully when the pedestrian signal is on, regardless of whether any
pedestrians are still waiting to cross the street.
Another concern with forcing pedestrians to wait for a signal is the area available for pedestrian
storage on the sidewalks adjacent to the crossing at Green Street. To gain the most benefit to
vehicular flow, pedestrians would have to wait until a walk signal is shown. During the time when
vehicular traffic has a green phase pedestrians must wait on the sidewalk. Due to the high volume
of pedestrians in this area there is not sufficient space on the sidewalk to accommodate both
queued pedestrians as well as those walking through the area.
Independent of a pedestrian signal, sidewalk curb extensions, should be constructed on each end
of the crosswalk. These will provide additional waiting area for pedestrians, as well as shortening
the crossing distance on Harvard Street, while improving the ability of pedestrians to see and be
seen by approaching traffic on Harvard Street. A conceptual curb extension layout, along with the
area available for pedestrian storage, is shown in Figure 4. Additionally, placing bollards or street
furniture along Harvard Street at the curb line between the Babcock Street and Green Street
intersections would discourage mid-block pedestrian crossings and would channelize pedestrian
flow to crosswalks at the intersections. Street furniture should be carefully situated so as not to
interfere with egress from the passenger side of parked vehicles.

text.i: Alternative 2 â€“ Improved Signal Coordination along Harvard Street

page.text: Preliminary design of a new coordination pattern shows that the conditions along Harvard Street
can be improved over the existing conditions. The existing traffic signal at Harvard Street and
Babcock Street is coordinated with the traffic signal at Beacon Street and Harvard Street in an
effort to improve traffic flow along Harvard Street. However, the existing coordination
parameters are based on traffic speeds of 30 mph on Harvard Street. Based on actual speed data
collected as part of this study, the average speeds on Harvard Street are 12-13 mph. This
difference between design speed and actual speeds results in many northbound vehicles on
Harvard Street arriving at the red light at Babcock Street, rather than the green light as intended.
To improve the progression and flow of traffic along Harvard Street it is recommended that the
signal offset at the Babcock Street intersection be adjusted to reflect the actual speeds on Harvard
Street. This will allow vehicles on Harvard Street to arrive at a green light at Babcock Street, even
after having to wait for pedestrians crossing at Green Street. This will help to reduce the vehicle
queueing on the northbound Harvard Street approach at the Babcock Street intersection. Timing
and phasing at the Beacon Street and Harvard Street intersection was not modified due to the
unseen effect any changes may have on coordination of signals along Beacon Street as well as the
MBTA Green Line operations. A measure of improvement can be seen by the decrease in travel
time for vehicles traveling the Harvard Street corridor between Beacon Street and Babcock Street.
The results of the travel time analysis are provided in Table 8.
As shown in Table 8, with the proposed coordination parameters in place to accommodate the
actual speed of vehicles, the overall travel time and delay in the northbound direction on Harvard
Street will decrease during all peak hours. The southbound direction will also experience a
decrease in travel time and delay during the evening and Saturday peak hour, with only a modest
increase in travel time during the morning peak hour.

text.i: Alternative 3 â€“ Lane Use Change â€“ Harvard Street NB at Beacon Street

page.text: As previously noted, the northbound Harvard Street approach at Beacon Street consists of one
through lane and one shared through/right turn lane (left turns onto Beacon Street are
prohibited). The shared through/right turn lane extends back to the Longwood Avenue
intersection, approximately 120 feet south of Beacon Street. The two through lanes then merge
back to a single lane north of Beacon Street, creating a bottleneck that contributes to vehicles
queuing into the Beacon Street intersection.
To remove this bottleneck, an alternative was analyzed to convert the existing northbound shared
through/right turn lane at the Beacon Street at Harvard Street intersection to an exclusive right
turn lane. Allowing only a single northbound lane through the intersection would serve to
eliminate the merge north of Beacon Street. To accommodate the heavier volume stacked in a
single through lane along northbound Harvard Street, six seconds of green time were shifted from
the Beacon Street approaches to the Harvard Street approaches. The effects of this change on the
Beacon Street coordinated signal system and Green Line trolley were not evaluated as part of this
study. The resulting levels of service and queues are shown in Table 9.

periods on all movements except the Harvard Street northbound through movement in the
morning peak period, which would degrade from LOS D under existing conditions to LOS E with
this change. However, during each peak period analyzed, 95
northbound Harvard Street approach would to extend well beyond the Longwood Avenue
intersection, located just 120 feet south of the Beacon Street intersection, causing queue spillback
that would affect operations along the Harvard Street corridor to the south.
Based on field observations, operations at the Beacon Street at Harvard Street intersection may
be improved by installing a signal at the Harvard Street at Longwood Avenue intersection
coordinated with the Beacon Street at Harvard Street intersection. This improvement would serve
to meter the volume of traffic entering the Beacon Street at Harvard Street intersection, allowing
the right lane on the northbound approach to be converted to an exclusive right turn lane without
causing queues along the northbound Harvard Street approach to extend through and block the
Longwood Avenue intersection. Additionally, field observations indicated that vehicles queues
along Harvard Street at the Longwood Avenue intersection currently obstruct sight distance
between drivers exiting the Longwood Avenue approach and pedestrians crossing Harvard Street
at this location. Installation of a coordinated signal at this intersection would create safe gaps in
the Harvard Street traffic flow to improve pedestrian safety at this location.
A pedestrian activated signal at the crosswalk at the intersection of Harvard Street and Green Street is not
recommended. The necessity of coordinating the pedestrian signal with the nearby signal at Beacon Street
would result in a signal that would not be responsive to pedestrian or vehicle needs. The signal would not
be able to change to the walk indication immediately, sometimes having to wait up to 40 seconds. The
result would be that many pedestrians would not wait for or obey the signal, and the actual delay to
motorists would increase as pedestrians first ignore the signal and cross against the light. This would result
in motorists arriving on a red signal after the pedestrians have already crossed the street.
Due to the high volume of pedestrians at the intersection, there is insufficient storage space for pedestrians
to wait up to 40 seconds when crossing Harvard Street. It is recommended that independent of the traffic
signal, curb extensions or sidewalk bump outs be constructed at each end of the crosswalk. These will
provide additional storage area for pedestrians, as well as shortening the crossing distance on Harvard
Street, while improving the ability of pedestrians to see and be seen by approaching traffic on Harvard
Street. Additionally, placing bollards or street furniture along Harvard Street at the curb line between the
Babcock Street and Green Street intersections would discourage mid-block pedestrian crossings and would
channelize pedestrian flow to crosswalks at the intersections.
With the actual speed of traffic on Harvard Street measured at 12-13 mph during the peak hours, it is
recommended that the coordination settings at the Babcock Street signal be modified to reflect the actual
speeds. This will allow traffic to progress along Harvard Street without encountering the red light at
Babcock Street as often, and will allow for shorter travel times and less delay between Beacon Street and
Babcock Street while still allowing for pedestrians to cross at Green Street without the need to wait for a
Finally, although converting the right lane from a shared through/right turn lane to an exclusive right turn
lane would eliminate the merge point on northbound Harvard Street north of Beacon Street, this change
is expected to result in operations along northbound Harvard Street at Beacon Street degrading from LOS
D to LOS E during the morning peak period, as well as creating queue spillback beyond the adjacent
unsignalized intersection of Harvard Street with Longwood Avenue intersection during the morning,
evening, and Saturday midday peak periods. The longest queues would occur during the morning peak
hour, reaching approximately 600 feet, or potentially beyond the intersection of Harvard Street with Sewall
Avenue and Stearns Road. Therefore, this change in lane assignment is not recommended without
additional changes in traffic control along Harvard Street south of Beacon Street to control vehicle queuing.
Based on field observations and preliminary investigation, it appears that this lane reassignment may e
feasible if a coordinated traffic signal were installed at the Harvard Street at Longwood Avenue
intersection. A signal at this location would meter traffic entering the Harvard Street at Beacon Street
intersection, controlling the aforementioned queue spillback. The resulting reduction in northbound
through lanes at the Beacon Street intersection would improve operations on northbound Harvard Street
by eliminating the merge point between the Beacon Street and Green Street intersections. In addition, a
signal at the Longwood Avenue intersection would facilitate safer accommodations for pedestrians
crossing Harvard Street at this location. It is recommended that the Town conduct a more in-depth
operational and safety analysis to explore the feasibility of signalizing the Harvard Street at Longwood
